  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">NIHR Global Health Research Group on Warfarin Anticoagulation in Patients with Cardiovascular Disease in Sub-Saharan Africa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Evaluate the quality of anticoagulant services in Cape Town and rural and urban Uganda. 2. Recruit patients currently on warfarin to identify clinical and other non-genetic factors associated with poor anticoagulation control. 3. Develop a warfarin clinical dosing algorithm. 4. Evaluate genes specific to the local African populations in Uganda and South Africa that can impact on anticoagulation control, and the development of a novel genetic dosing algorithm. 5. Initiate a study to implement the clinical dosing algorithm in the two sites. Objectives for new work packages are: 
1. Develop protocols and guidance documents for the bundle, according to SQUIRE guidelines
(squirestatement.org) and attain necessary governance approvals; 2. Develop locally-appropriate training packages to ensure hospital staff are aware of the bundle aims to support adherence and educate patients; 3. Work with local patient groups to co-create tools to support adherence and educate patients; 4. Implement the bundle in hospitals (in Kampala &amp; Cape Town) and their down-referral anticoagulation clinics; 5. Assess the clinical effectiveness and cost effectiveness of the bundle; 6. Assess staff and patient views on the bundle.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">A UK and low- and middle-income country (LMIC) partnership that aims to improve anticoagulation with warfarin - an important area of unmet medical need in LMICs - by developing context-appropriate dosing algorithms, and further improve anticoagulation quality by using novel technological advances.</narrative>
  </description>
